    <text>
        <body>
            <div style="handwritten" type="letter">
                <head type="title">Miklós Oláh to Camillo Ghilino (Brussels, 13 April 1534)</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p>Ambrogio Candiano, the Sforzas’ physician, has arrived to them. He seems
                            to be worthy of the task of healing the Queen, who has recovered so much
                            that she can ride again. He has received the treasurer’s quarters and
                            table for his use. Ghilino’s horse is well, they have sent it to Antwerp
                            to the treasurer of Ghilino’s lord, but he is not riding it any more: he
                            is dead. He will try to send his horse to him. Jemme Reinerszoon’s globe
                            is not perfect yet. Conrad Wackers is trying to hurry up the artist, but
                            Ghilino also knows how shrewd the Brabantians are – he will take care of
                            this, too.</p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb/>
                <p>Nicolai Olai ad Camillum Gilinum a Secretis Francisci <del
                        corresp="Olahus">Scorciae</del><add corresp="Olahus" type="corr"
                        >Sforciae</add> ducis Mediolanensis. </p>
                <p><del corresp="Olahus">Salve!</del> Litterarum illarum, de quibus olim
                    locuti fuimus, γνωμόνικος<note type="critic">‘competent’.</note> Elegantissime
                    et Strenuissime: <add corresp="Olahus" type="insert">Salve!</add>
                    <persName>Medicus</persName><note type="critic">Ambrogio Candiano was Francesco
                        II Maria Sforza’s physician, and he also healed Queen Mary of Hungary, see
                            <hi rend="smallcap">Tiraboschi</hi> 1796, 626. In the poem addressed to
                        Candiano, Oláh called him Angelus Candianus, see <hi rend="smallcap"
                            >Hegedüs</hi> 1906, 396–398; <hi rend="smallcap">Fógel–Juhász</hi> 1934,
                        18–19; <hi rend="smallcap">Neagu</hi> 2003, 316–317.</note> illustrissimi
                        <persName>ducis</persName><note type="critic">Francesco II Sforza.</note>
                    tui, quem tanto desiderio exspectabamus, aliquot post tuum a nobis discessum
                    diebus ad nos applicuit. Dignus sane, ut videtur, vir, cui
                        <persName>reginae</persName> valetudo committatur, quae iam ad equitationem
                    usque convaluit. Domus et tabula quaestoris nostri est illi designata, qua
                    uteretur ex animi sui sententia. Scis enim eos, qui pecuniam tractant, lautiores
                    solere esse hospites. Equus tuus convaluit, quem miseramus
                        <placeName>Antwerpiam</placeName>
                    <milestone unit="pb"/> ad <persName>ducis</persName> tui
                        <persName>quaestorem</persName>,<note type="critic">According to Ghilino’s
                        answer, his name was Monbelli. We do not know him more closely.</note> sed
                    ille maluit <persName>Charontis</persName><note type="critic">In Greek
                        mythology, Kharon carries the souls across the river Styx.</note> naviculam,
                    quam equum tuum equitare: dicitur enim vita esse functus. Curabimus tamen cum
                        <persName>Banisio</persName>,<note type="critic">Probably Jakob Radich de
                        Bannisis the Younger.</note> ut equus ad te perveniat. Globus<note
                        type="critic">On the globe Jemme Reinerszoon made for Ghilino, see <hi
                            rend="smallcap">Smet</hi> 1966/1967, 228–229.</note> ille caelestis
                    nondum perfectus est. <persName>Goclenius</persName><note type="critic">Conrad
                        Wackers.</note> artificem sollicitat, sed scis vafritiem<note type="critic"
                        >Early modern form, as opposed to the classical <hi rend="italic"
                            >vafritia</hi>, see <hi rend="smallcap">Ramminger</hi> 2008.</note>
                    hominum Brabantinorum. Ultra praefinitam mercedem nescio, quid pluris somniat,
                    dicit te non satisfecisse <persName>Gemmae</persName>,<note type="critic">Jemme
                        Reinerszoon.</note> quod tibi annulorum artificium et legem demonstrarit.
                    Vide hominis impudentiam! Conficiemus tamen id quoque cum eo.
                        <persName>Banisius</persName> profectus est heri
                        <placeName>Lovanium</placeName>. Cui, si nihil per hunc baliolum ad te
                    scripserit, veniam dabis. Nova hic nulla, si quae istic habetis, fac me
                    certiorem. Vale, Olai non immemor tui ex corde amantis. Commenda me, si
                    aliquando occasio oblata fuerit, <del corresp="Olahus">magnifico</del> duci tuo.
                    Vale iterum. </p>
                <p><placeName>Bruxellae</placeName> 13. Aprilis 1534.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
